284
30:52.020 --> 30:58.470
So U being unitary is equivalent to the columns forming an orthonormal set,

285
30:58.470 --> 31:05.070
And that has to be a basis because the number of vectors in the set, which is three in this case, agrees with the dimension of the space

286
31:05.070 --> 31:12.810
that we're working in. You can follow a similar argument for the rows instead of the columns to conclude that U being
unitary is equivalent

287
31:12.810 --> 31:16.170
to the rows farming an orthonormal basis.

288
31:16.170 --> 31:23.910
It doesn't work quite as nicely because we have to make an adjustment to get the complex conjugates
to work in the right way, but the idea is the same.

289
31:23.910 --> 31:31.740
An alternative way to go about it, which is pretty straightforward, is to prove that a matrix is unitary if and only if it's transposed as unitary.

290
31:31.740 --> 31:36.120
And here I do mean to say transpose and not conjugate transpose.

291
31:36.120 --> 31:42.480
It's pretty trivial from the
definition of unitary matrices, that the conjugate transpose
of any unitary matrix is unitary,

292
31:42.480 --> 31:49.500
but it's also the case that the transpose of any unitary matrix is unitary.

293
31:49.500 --> 31:57.210
In any case, we have the
equivalence between these three conditions on any square matrix U, and we can combine this equivalence

294
31:57.210 --> 32:03.570
with the fact about
extending orthonormal sets to form orthonormal bases in order to come up with unitary matrices

295
32:03.570 --> 32:09.750
that do interesting things
or fulfill various needs that we may encounter.

296
32:09.750 --> 32:16.140
Specifically anytime we
have an orthonormal set of M vectors, there will always exist a unitary matrix U

297
32:16.140 --> 32:21.870
whose first M columns are the vectors from that orthonormal set.

298
32:21.870 --> 32:28.130
The remaining columns
can always be filled in so that we obtain a unitary matrix by choosing them so that the columns form

299
32:28.130 --> 32:35.790
an orthonormal basis. This will be a pretty
handy fact for us to have at our disposal.

300
32:35.790 --> 32:42.944
And one more topic for
this section of the lesson is the notion of a projection.

301
32:42.944 --> 32:51.660
A square matrix Pi is
said to be a projection or a projection matrix if the two properties that
are listed here are both true.

302
32:51.660 --> 32:58.470
This is a capital Pi by the way, it's a pretty typical choice for a letter that's used to denote a projection.

303
32:58.470 --> 33:04.980
We often give these typical sorts of names to objects such as matrices just to make them easier to recognize and keep things straight,

304
33:04.980 --> 33:13.440
but you could use whatever name you like. Anyway, the first condition is that Pi is equal to its own conjugate transpose.

305
33:13.440 --> 33:19.500
In general, when we have a matrix that's equal to its own
conjugate transpose, we say that it's a Hermitian matrix.

306
33:19.500 --> 33:24.510
So the first condition can alternatively be stated as Pi is Hermitian.

307
33:24.510 --> 33:31.110
The second condition is
that if we square Pi, meaning that we multiply Pi
to itself, we get Pi again.

308
33:31.110 --> 33:35.520
So squaring Pi doesn't do anything to it.

309
33:35.520 --> 33:44.070
The idea of a projection
intuitively speaking is that it's similar in
spirit to projecting an image onto a screen or dropping
a perpendicular onto a line

310
33:44.070 --> 33:50.250
for instance. When you multiply a
vector by a projection, what you're doing is in some sense

311
33:50.250 --> 33:53.760
leaving a part of it alone
and zeroing out the rest.

312
33:53.760 --> 34:02.250
So if you apply a
projection a second time, it doesn't do anything because
you've already zeroed out the part that the projection zeroes out.

313
34:02.250 --> 34:08.940
An example of a projection
is this matrix right here for any choice of a unit vector Psi.

314
34:08.940 --> 34:13.830
We can check that it satisfies
the required conditions one at a time.

315
34:13.830 --> 34:20.280
For the first one, we compute
the conjugate transpose and this is the conjugate
transpose of a product.

316
34:20.280 --> 34:26.460
And so we can use this formula right here for the conjugate transpose
of a product to help us.

317
34:26.460 --> 34:31.650
What you get is the product
of the conjugate transposes, but the order gets reversed.

318
34:31.650 --> 34:35.010
That happens because of
the transposition part.

319
34:35.010 --> 34:44.190
So if we apply that formula, we obtain this equality right here and we can then simplify to
get back the original matrix.

320
34:44.190 --> 34:47.340
Notice by the way, that we didn't use the fact
that Psi is a unit vector.

321
34:47.340 --> 34:54.180
So in fact, this matrix is
Hermitian for any vector Psi, not just for unit vectors.

322
34:54.180 --> 35:01.080
And for the second one, we square Pi and we obtain
this expression right here and that is equal to the
original matrix this time

323
35:01.080 --> 35:08.310
because Psi is a unit vector, so this inner product
right here is equal to one and that's where the assumption
that Psi is a unit vector

324
35:08.310 --> 35:12.300
comes into play.

325
35:12.300 --> 35:16.050
We can generalize this example and start with an orthonormal set.

326
35:16.050 --> 35:24.990
And if we form this matrix right here, where we sum up the projections corresponding to the individual vectors, then we obtain a projection.

327
35:24.990 --> 35:31.290
Here on the screen, you can see calculations that reveal that and I'll leave it to you to
examine them if you wish.

328
35:31.290 --> 35:38.940
And along similar lines
to the first example, it's the second condition where the orthonormality
of the set gets used.

329
35:38.940 --> 35:46.980
What this projection does if
you multiply it to a vector, is to project that
vector onto the subspace that's spanned by this set of vectors,

330
35:46.980 --> 35:56.130
which in an abstract way is
like dropping a perpendicular to that subspace, and once
you're in that subspace, the projection doesn't do anything.

331
35:56.130 --> 36:03.000
So matrices like this are
examples of projections, and now in fact we've exhausted
all of the possibilities.

332
36:03.000 --> 36:07.920
Every projection matrix takes this form for some choice of an orthonormal set.

333
36:07.920 --> 36:13.590
The zero matrix is a projection, so we do have to make
sure we include that one if we want to get every projection.

